body:
https://issues.apache.org/jira/browse/SOLR-15587

This also fixes: https://issues.apache.org/jira/browse/SOLR-15364 ... in short, what a damn mess this has become :P

This PR is basically reverting the feature flag that determined if `base_url` was persisted to Zookeeper or not. Given the current design, it **MUST** be stored! Moreover, client applications should not be affected by the singleton `UrlScheme` which really should only apply on the server. UrlScheme isn't actually needed on the server either, so this PR removes it entirely, due to issues like this: https://github.com/apache/lucene-solr/pull/2010#issuecomment-996257742

An alternative approach that I briefly considered was to have the client-side `ClusterState` set the `base_url` based on the `node_name` and the `urlScheme` cluster property on replicas as it reads them from the server. However, that only helps if the client application is running the latest SolrJ, but we don't mandate that for Solr. For instance, it's reasonable that users may upgrade their servers to Solr 8.11.2 (which should have this fix) but not their client applications, which may be running SolrJ 8.7.x or something without this fix. So I still think the best course of action is to just store the `base_url` in ZK as a primary property of a replica and if users need to switch from `http` to `https`, then they'll have to mutate the stored state in ZK manually (which has always been the case).

Verified the changes with some additional manual testing, including:

- Rolling upgrade from 3 node 8.7.0 cluster (with https enabled) to a build from this branch
- SolrJ client app that uses the `HttpClusterStateProvider`, basically:
```
try (CloseableHttpClient httpClient = HttpClientUtil.createClient(null)) {
            ClusterStateProvider stateProvider = new HttpClusterStateProvider(Collections.singletonList(solrUrl), httpClient);
            String urlScheme = (String)stateProvider.getClusterProperty("urlScheme");
            System.out.println(">> from HTTP cluster state, urlScheme: "+urlScheme);
            DocCollection dc = stateProvider.getClusterState().getCollection("sop2");
            List<Replica> replicas = dc.getReplicas();
            System.out.println(">> replicas: "+replicas);
}
```
- SolrJ client app that uses the `ZkClusterStateProvider` (to verify no regression)
